Title: 189/32: Baltimore -- Buildings -- State Tobacco Warehouse, circa 1910-1930
Description: 189/32: Baltimore -- Buildings -- State Tobacco Warehouse, circa 1910-1930. (Item 3 - Barrels and barrels of tobacco line the streets outside the State Tobacco Warehouse, Baltimore, Maryland, August 1919. The newspaper article heading for this picture says: "Largest Tobacco Crop In State's History." Newspaper cation reads: "The 1918 crop of Maryland tobacco is now being inspected at the State Tobacco Warehouses, Charles and Conway streets, and according to an official there it is one of the largest crops in the history of the tobacco industry in this State. Practically all this tobacco has been raised in Southern Maryland, coming from Anne Arundel, Prince George's, Charles, Calvert and St. Mary's counties. An extra large force of inspectors has been working continuously at the warehouses. It is estimated the crop will total 19,000 hogsheads. After undergoing inspection and being stamped with the Government seals the tobacco will be shipped to all parts of the world. The American Tobacco Company and the R. J. Reynolds Tobacco Company, it was said, have placed big orders for Maryland tobacco. This is unusual, as these companies in the past got most of their goods farther South. Most of the Maryland tobacco is shipped here by steamers of the Patuxent river route, a little coming by other lines and by rail. One of the inspectors said today that, owing to the termination of the war, a large percentage of the tobacco will be shipped abroad. Some of it will go to Holland, France, Italy, Denmark, and some may go to Germany through Holland.")

Title: Summer dance class, University of Maryland, July 21,1940
Description: University of Maryland students dancing outdoors as part of a summer dance class, July 21, 1940. Caption reads: "Some fellows get all the breaks. For instance, those nine University of Maryland men who are enrolled with 35 women students in a dancing class, believed the first of its sort offered in an Eastern institution of the higher learning. That these U. of Md. dancing damsels know their eurythmics, a glance--if you can content yourself with a glance--at the above panorama will attest. The masculine performers also evince grace and elan. Decidedly a terpsichorean treat. The dancing instruction is part of the university's summer curriculum. Title: Katherine Anne Porter in wide-brimmed hat and white gloves holding carved coconut banks, Mexico, circa November-December, 1964
Description: Katherine Anne Porter in a wide-brimmed hat and white gloves holding carved coconut banks. A three-footed pottery bowl and another Mexican artisania sits on the table in front of her, Mexico. circa November-December 1964. Statement (in Spanish) on back reads: "Katherine Anne Porter, escritora norteamericana y maestra, arribara a la ciudad de Mexico el viernes 20 de noviembre con el objeto de sustentar una serie de platicas y concurrir a reuniones con escritotres durante su permanencia en el pais, que se prolongara hasta el 4 de diciembre proximo. La senorita Porter hablara en ele Instituto Mexicano-Norteamericano de Relaciones Culturales; en el Centro Mexicano de Escritores y en la Universidad Nacional Autonoma de Mexico. El viaje de la senorita Porter lo patrocina el Programa de Intercambio de Presentaciones Culturales del Departamento de Estado de lost Estados Unidos."

Title: Katherine Anne Porter standing outside her house, Mixcoac, Mexico, October 27, 1930
Description: Photograph of Katherine Anne Porter by Manuel Alvarez Bravo standing outside her house in Mixocoac, Mexico, an ancient Indian town near Mexico City, October 27, 1930. Back inscription reads: "This photograph taken in Mixcoac, ancient Indian town near Mexico City, against the wall of my house in morning sunlight, late summer 1930. No make-up, no retouching, Manuel Alvarez Bravo was then young, just setting out on his life work. He has become a famous photographer."
